FeatNavigator: Automatic Feature Augmentation on Tabular Data

Jiaming Liang1∗, Chuan Lei2, Xiao Qin2, Jiani Zhang2,
Asterios Katsifodimos2,3, Christos Faloutsos2,4, Huzefa Rangwala2 1University of Pennsylvania, 2AWS AI Research & Education, 3TU Delft, 4Carnegie Mellon University
liangjm@seas.upenn.edu, {chuanlei, drxqin, zhajiani, akatsifo, faloutso, rhuzefa}@amazon.com
Abstract.

Data-centric AI focuses on understanding and utilizing high-quality, relevant data in training machine learning (ML) models, thereby increasing the likelihood of producing accurate and useful results. Automatic feature augmentation, aiming to augment the initial base table with useful features from other tables, is critical in data preparation as it improves model performance, robustness, and generalizability. While recent works have investigated automatic feature augmentation, most of them have limited capabilities in utilizing all useful features as many of them are in candidate tables not directly joinable with the base table. Worse yet, with numerous join paths leading to these distant features, existing solutions fail to fully exploit them within a reasonable compute budget.

We present FeatNavigator, an effective and efficient framework that explores and integrates high-quality features in relational tables for ML models. FeatNavigator evaluates a feature from two aspects: (1) the intrinsic value of a feature towards an ML task (i.e., feature importance) and (2) the efficacy of a join path connecting the feature to the base table (i.e., integration quality). FeatNavigator strategically selects a small set of available features and their corresponding join paths to train a feature importance estimation model and an integration quality prediction model. Furthermore, FeatNavigator’s search algorithm exploits both estimated feature importance and integration quality to identify the optimized feature augmentation plan. Our experimental results show that FeatNavigator outperforms state-of-the-art solutions on five public datasets by up to 40.1% in ML model performance.

1. Introduction

Feature augmentation is a crucial process that enhances machine learning (ML) model performance (Kanter and Veeramachaneni, 2015; Chepurko et al., 2020; Liu et al., 2022; Galhotra et al., 2023). The process of feature augmentation on tabular data typically involves feature exploration and integration. Feature exploration identifies useful features among candidate tables that could reveal additional insights or patterns. And feature integration decides how to join the selected candidate tables with the base table to augment the initial training data. Open tabular data repositories such as Google Dataset Search111https://datasetsearch.research.google.com/, Kaggle222https://www.kaggle.com/datasets, and OpenML333https://www.openml.org/ provide diverse tabular data that capture a wide range of features. By exploring and integrating features from these repositories of data, ML models can generalize to more patterns (Chen et al., 2020), overcome overfitting (Ying, 2019), thereby leading to improved performance on unseen data (Chepurko et al., 2020; Liu et al., 2022; Galhotra et al., 2023).

Motivating Example. Figure 1 shows an example of feature augmentation on a toy dataset with a classification task. The base table is product, in which recommend is the target column, indicating whether the product should be recommended or not. The tables category, rating, review, and order are directly joinable with product. And collection, dispute and customer are candidate tables indirectly joinable with product through the other tables. Assuming that the features (e.g., address) from customer are useful to the prediction task, three join paths can be used to augment the base table product. However, these paths are not equivalent as customers may not provide ratings or reviews for all purchased products. In fact, the join path, customer ⋈⋈\bowtie order ⋈⋈\bowtie product (indicated by the thick red line), provides the highest quality to augment the base table. One can only discover that by actually joining these tables, which can be expensive when involving multiple large tables. When the prior knowledge about feature importance is missing, it becomes more challenging to examine all candidate tables, including both directly and indirectly joinable ones. Expensive joins need to be executed in order to find out the actual benefit of an augmented table to the prediction task. Worse yet, certain joins (e.g., product ⋈⋈\bowtie category and product ⋈⋈\bowtie rating indicated by the thick orange lines) are repeated multiple times when exploring different tables.

State-of-the-art Approaches. Early works (Kumar et al., 2016; Chepurko et al., 2020) augment the base table by joining other tables based on either their relevancy to the base table or the improvement of the contained features bring to the ML models. However, they assume that the features and their respective relevance to the base table are specified. Hence they fail to leverage all possible candidate feature and consequently do not reach the optimal model performance. Recently, ALITE (Khatiwada et al., 2022) and DIALITE (Khatiwada et al., 2023b) are introduced to integrate tables based on joinability or unionability, which can improve the quality of downstream applications (e.g., ML models).

Reinforcement learning (RL) (Vermorel and Mohri, 2005; Wang et al., 2016) has emerged as an effective approach to balance between feature exploration and exploitation. Several studies (Liu et al., 2022; Chai et al., 2022; Galhotra et al., 2023) leverage RL techniques, such as multi-armed bandits and Deep Q Networks (DQNs), to explore the large search space of candidate tables. Although these RL-based methods have achieved promising results, they still face critical challenges. Specifically, METAM (Galhotra et al., 2023) is limited to direct joinable candidate tables and AutoFeature (Liu et al., 2022) does not provide fine-grained optimization on integration quality. Moreover, RL often relies on a large number of samples to learn effectively (DQNs in particular), and tends to overfit to the training environment, leading to poor performance in slightly different real-world situations.

Challenges. Based on the above observations, we aim to address the following open challenges.

  1. (1)

    Integration Quality. In real-world open data settings, a candidate table can be integrated with the base table via multiple join paths, which often have very different integration quality. Hence, it is critical to identify the optimal join path to achieve the full potential (i.e., feature importance) of a candidate table.

  2. (2)

    Expensive Join Operations. Join operations are computationally expensive and time consuming, especially when a long join path involves multiple joins. Candidate tables from open data repositories often share similar join paths. Therefore, avoiding or sharing join operations is imperative to efficient feature augmentation.

  3. (3)

    Search Complexity. The search space of all candidate tables along with all integration paths is intractable, making it prohibitively expensive to find the optimal set of candidate tables. To address this challenge, we need effective strategies to reduce the search space without compromising optimality.

Proposed Solution. To cope with the above mentioned challenges, we propose FeatNavigator, an efficient and effective framework for automatic feature augmentation. Given a base table, a set of candidate tables and a ML task, FeatNavigator first effectively selects a subset of candidate tables using a lightweight clustering algorithm based on table characteristics (e.g., embeddings, statistics, semantics, etc.). FeatNavigator further chooses representative join paths from these candidate tables to the base table. This allows FeatNavigator to not only find out the actual performance gain led by the candidate tables following the join paths but also learn an integration quality model and a feature importance estimator to calculate the performance gain of any unexplored candidate tables and their respective join paths. Lastly, FeatNavigator’s path search algorithm utilizes the integration quality model and feature importance estimator to further prune the search space and finds the optimized integration paths for the selected candidate tables in polynomial time. In case of having new tables added or table updates to the data repository, FeatNavigator’s integration quality model and feature importance estimator can effectively and efficiently estimate the performance gain without retraining. In polynomial time, FeatNavigator’s search algorithm produces new optimized integration paths if the estimated performance gain is higher than the one of the existing paths.

Contributions. Our main contributions are the following.

  1. (1)

    We introduce FeatNavigator, a novel feature augmentation framework designed for ML tasks over tabular data repositories.

  2. (2)

    We decompose the intractable problem of feature augmentation into two sub-problems, feature importance and integration quality, and consequently prove the relationship between them.

  3. (3)

    We design an effective feature exploration module consisting of a lightweight clustering-based feature importance estimation and an effective LSTM-based integration quality model.

  4. (4)

    We propose an efficient feature path search algorithm that exploits both estimated feature importance and integration quality to identify high-quality features and their optimized join paths for integration.

  5. (5)

    Our experiments show that FeatNavigator outperforms state-of-the-art baselines on different ML tasks over five public datasets with up to 40.1% improvement ML model performance.

2. Preliminaries and System Overview

In this section, we first discuss the notions used in this paper, formally define the problem of feature augmentation and then provide an overview of FeatNavigator.

2.1. Basic Notions

Definition 2.1 (Base Table).

The base table, Tbasesubscript𝑇baseT_{\textit{base}} = {c1subscript𝑐1c_{1}, c2subscript𝑐2c_{2}, …, cnsubscript𝑐𝑛c_{n}, clsubscript𝑐𝑙c_{l}}, refers to the original table that includes the initial set of features and the label column before any augmentation. Each cisubscript𝑐𝑖c_{i} (i∈𝑖absenti\in [1, n𝑛n]) represents a column and clsubscript𝑐𝑙c_{l} denotes the label column, which stores the prediction target for each row.

Definition 2.2 (Candidate Tables).

The candidate tables, 𝒯𝒯\mathcal{T} = {T1subscript𝑇1T_{1}, T2subscript𝑇2T_{2}, …, Tmsubscript𝑇𝑚T_{m}}, are m𝑚m joinable tables that can be used to augment a base table Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base}. Each table is denoted by Tjsubscript𝑇𝑗T_{j} = {fj,1subscript𝑓𝑗1f_{j,1}, fj,2subscript𝑓𝑗2f_{j,2}, …, fj,ksubscript𝑓𝑗𝑘f_{j,k}} (j∈𝑗absentj\in [1, m𝑚m]), where fj,ksubscript𝑓𝑗𝑘f_{j,k} denotes the k𝑘k-th column (a.k.a feature)444We use two terms, column and feature, alternately in this paper. in table Tjsubscript𝑇𝑗T_{j}.

Definition 2.3 (Join Path).

Given a set of tables T1,T2,…,Tnsubscript𝑇1subscript𝑇2…subscript𝑇𝑛T_{1},T_{2},\ldots,T_{n}, a join path P𝑃P can be defined as a sequence of join operations between pairs of tables. A join operation between any two tables Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i} and Tjsubscript𝑇𝑗T_{j} can be denoted as Ti⋈Tj⋈subscript𝑇𝑖subscript𝑇𝑗T_{i}\bowtie T_{j}. The join path P𝑃P can be represented as: P=T1⋈T2⋈T3​…⋈Tn𝑃subscript𝑇1⋈subscript𝑇2⋈subscript𝑇3…⋈subscript𝑇𝑛P=T_{1}\bowtie T_{2}\bowtie T_{3}\ldots\bowtie T_{n}.

Hence a join path between the base table Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base} and a candidate table Tcsubscript𝑇𝑐T_{c} can be expressed as: P=Tb​a​s​e⋈Ti⋈Ti+1​…⋈Tc𝑃subscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒⋈subscript𝑇𝑖⋈subscript𝑇𝑖1…⋈subscript𝑇𝑐P=T_{base}\bowtie T_{i}\bowtie T_{i+1}\ldots\bowtie T_{c}. Without loss of generality, we allow different types of join operators between the base table Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base} and a candidate table Tc∈𝒯subscript𝑇𝑐𝒯T_{c}\in\mathcal{T}, including inner join, left outer join, right outer join, etc.

Definition 2.4 (Augmented Table).

The augmented table Ta​u​gsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔T_{aug} is the result of joining the base table Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base} and a candidate table Tcsubscript𝑇𝑐T_{c} following a join path P𝑃P.

Note that there can be multiple join paths between the base table and a candidate table. Hence the augmented table could be different depending on the chosen join path.

Definition 2.5 (Machine Learning Task).

A machine learning (ML) task is defined as a function f𝑓f that maps an input space 𝒳𝒳\mathcal{X} to an output space 𝒴𝒴\mathcal{Y}. Given a dataset D={(x1,y1),(x2,y2),…,(xn,yn)}𝐷subscript𝑥1subscript𝑦1subscript𝑥2subscript𝑦2…subscript𝑥𝑛subscript𝑦𝑛D=\{(x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2}),\ldots,(x_{n},y_{n})\}, where xi∈𝒳subscript𝑥𝑖𝒳x_{i}\in\mathcal{X} and yi∈𝒴subscript𝑦𝑖𝒴y_{i}\in\mathcal{Y}, the objective is to learn the function f𝑓f that best approximates the true underlying relationship from the inputs to the outputs. For a classification task, we have f:𝒳→𝒴:𝑓→𝒳𝒴f:\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y}, where 𝒴𝒴\mathcal{Y} is a discrete set of labels. For a regression task, we have f:𝒳→ℝ:𝑓→𝒳ℝf:\mathcal{X}\to\mathbb{R}, where 𝒴𝒴\mathcal{Y} is a continuous domain.

Definition 2.6 (Utility Gain).

Given a ML task, the utility score, U​S​(T)𝑈𝑆𝑇US(T), is defined as the objective or performance metric (e.g., accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score, etc.) of the task on a table T𝑇T achieved by a specific ML model. Note that U​S​(T)𝑈𝑆𝑇US(T) uses the negation of a metric value when smaller values are preferred (e.g., mean squared error (MSE), mean absolute error (MAE), etc.). Let U​S​(Tb​a​s​e)𝑈𝑆subscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒US(T_{base}) be the performance metric on the base table, and U​S​(Ta​u​g)𝑈𝑆subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔US(T_{aug}) be the performance metric on the augmented table. The utility gain U​G𝑈𝐺UG is defined as the improvement in the performance metric: U​G=U​S​(Ta​u​g)−U​S​(Tb​a​s​e)𝑈𝐺𝑈𝑆subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔𝑈𝑆subscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒UG=US(T_{aug})-US(T_{base}).

Problem Statement. Given a base table Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base}, a set of candidate tables 𝒯𝒯\mathcal{T}, and a ML task, our goal is to select a subset of tables from 𝒯𝒯\mathcal{T} and to identify the best join paths to augment with Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base}, such that the utility gain U​G𝑈𝐺UG of the ML task on Ta​u​gsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔T_{aug} is maximized.

The complexity of choosing a subset of tables (i.e., feature selection) generally increases exponentially with the number of candidate tables (features), as all possible combinations of features need to be evaluated, making the problem NP-hard. Even with various heuristic and optimization techniques (John et al., 1994; Battiti, 1994) to reduce the complexity, the cost of feature selection can be still expensive. Worse yet, enumerating all possible join paths among the base and candidate tables is prohibitively expensive due to its exponential time complexity in the worst case. The combination of these two exponential search spaces makes the problem intractable, consequently needing an effective and efficient method.

2.2. FeatNavigator System Overview

For a given ML task, FeatNavigator takes input as a base table with a prediction task on the target column and a tabular data repository consisting of candidate tables with features. FeatNavigator leverages data discovery systems such as Aurum (Fernandez et al., 2018) or NYU Auctus (Castelo et al., 2021) to identify the candidate tables within k𝑘k-hop joins to the base tables. FeatNavigator then triggers its utility gain model in two stages.

In the exploration stage, FeatNavigator takes the following four steps. (1) It first groups the identified features into clusters based on their representations (embeddings, data distributions, types, etc.) using an efficient clustering algorithm. (2) To train the integration quality model, FeatNavigator employs a path selection strategy to choose a number of features and candidate join paths. (3) FeatNavigator then follows the selected join paths to integrate the target features into the base table and runs AutoML (e.g., AutoGluon555https://auto.gluon.ai/) to find out the actual utility gain compared to the model performance only using the base table. (4) FeatNavigator effectively collects a sufficient amount of training data to train the integration quality model and also assigns the actual feature importance to the selected features in the clusters. The importance of the other features can be estimated based on their relative distance to the ones with the actual importance assigned.

In the exploitation stage, FeatNavigator leverages both a feature importance estimator and an integration quality model to conduct an efficient and effective search over all identified features and their associated join paths. It iteratively selects the most important feature and uses the integration quality model to select the optimal join path (i.e., best integration quality) until a predefined number of features is reached. FeatNavigator then follows the selected join paths to integrate the selected features with the base table and generates the final augmented table for the given ML task. Finally, AutoML solutions (e.g., AutoGluon) can train, select and deploy the best performing machine learning model on the augmented table (Erickson et al., 2020).

3. Utility Gain Modeling

As discussed in Section 2.1, the problem of maximizing utility gain for a given ML task is intractable. Hence we propose to decompose this problem into two sub-problems, namely maximizing feature importance and maximizing integration quality. The motivation behind this decomposition is that the effectiveness of a candidate feature relies on two critical factors, namely (1) feature importance – how useful is a feature to the ML model if it can be fully leveraged (e.g., the significance of product ratings in the context of product recommendations), and (2) integration quality – how many data instances in the base table can be augmented by a feature from a candidate table. In the rest of this section, we will introduce several key concepts to help define these two factors and use them together to derive the decomposition and our final optimization goal. The detailed algorithms for achieving the derived optimization goal are then introduced in the next section.

Feature Importance. To define the feature importance, we first introduce the concept of a virtual table. Let Ta​u​gsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔T_{aug} denote a resulting augmented table from a base table Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base} and a candidate table Tcsubscript𝑇𝑐T_{c}. The virtual table Tv​i​r​tsubscript𝑇𝑣𝑖𝑟𝑡T_{virt} refers to the ideal case where there exists a join path P𝑃P such that every instance in Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base} can be augmented by a feature instance from Tcsubscript𝑇𝑐T_{c} via this P𝑃P (i.e., iPhone 15 with a rating of 5, Pixel 8 with a rating of 4.5, and Galaxy S23 with a rating of 4 shown in Figure 3(b)). Note that a virtual table is specific to a base table and an individual candidate feature.

Definition 3.1 (Feature Importance).

Feature importance is defined as the largest utility gain achievable by augmenting the base table with a candidate feature fi,j∈Tisubscript𝑓𝑖𝑗subscript𝑇𝑖f_{i,j}\in T_{i}, i.e.,

F​I​(fi,j)=U​S​(Tv​i​r​t​(i,j))−U​S​(Tb​a​s​e),𝐹𝐼subscript𝑓𝑖𝑗𝑈𝑆subscript𝑇𝑣𝑖𝑟𝑡𝑖𝑗𝑈𝑆subscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒FI(f_{i,j})=US(T_{virt(i,j)})-US(T_{base}),

where fi,jsubscript𝑓𝑖𝑗f_{i,j} is the j𝑗j-th feature from the table Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i}, Tv​i​r​t​(i,j)subscript𝑇𝑣𝑖𝑟𝑡𝑖𝑗T_{virt(i,j)} is the virtual table augmented by the feature fi,jsubscript𝑓𝑖𝑗f_{i,j} and F​I​(fi,j)𝐹𝐼subscript𝑓𝑖𝑗FI(f_{i,j}) ranges from -1 to 1.

F​I​(⋅)𝐹𝐼⋅FI(\cdot) quantifies the (positive or negative) impact of a candidate feature to the ML task on the base table. Note that the value of F​I​(⋅)𝐹𝐼⋅FI(\cdot) depends on the corresponding metric used by the utility score.

Integration Quality. On the other hand, integration quality measures the number of feature instances that can be carried over into the base table via a particular join path. It quantifies the proportion of instances in the base table that can be successfully augmented by the candidate table. For example, Figures 3(c) and 3(d) show two augmented tables using the same feature rating. The join path P1subscript𝑃1P_{1} = product ⋈⋈\bowtie transaction_1 ⋈⋈\bowtie rating brings 2 out of 4 instances from the rating table to the product table. However, only 1 instance from the rating table can be augmented to the base table by following P2subscript𝑃2P_{2} = product ⋈⋈\bowtie transaction_2 ⋈⋈\bowtie rating. Hence P1subscript𝑃1P_{1} is a better integration path than P2subscript𝑃2P_{2}.

When data instances in the base table cannot be augmented by a candidate feature, we use the special token null to fill the missing feature value, which will be used for the modeling training and evaluation. Note that AutoML solutions such as AutoGluon can automatically handle missing values during model training (Erickson et al., 2020). Therefore, an augmented table can be split into two parts, namely non-NA and NA. non-NA refers to the set of instances in Ta​u​gsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔T_{aug} that are augmented by feature instances, and NA denote the data instances in Ta​u​gsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔T_{aug} filled with null values. For example, in Figure 3(c), two products p​1𝑝1p1 and p​2𝑝2p2 in the red box belong to non-NA, and the other product p​3𝑝3p3 composes the NA.

Definition 3.2 (Integration Quality).

Integration quality of an augmented table Ta​u​gsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔T_{aug} is defined as a ratio between the number of feature instances that contribute to the augmentation and the total number of instances in the base table through a specific join path:

I​Q​(Ta​u​g)=|non-NA||Ta​u​g|=#​a​u​g​m​e​n​t​e​d​i​n​s​t​a​n​c​e​s#​i​n​s​t​a​n​c​e​s​ in ​Ta​u​g,𝐼𝑄subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔non-NAsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔#𝑎𝑢𝑔𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑑𝑖𝑛𝑠𝑡𝑎𝑛𝑐𝑒𝑠#𝑖𝑛𝑠𝑡𝑎𝑛𝑐𝑒𝑠 in subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔IQ(T_{aug})=\frac{|\textit{non-NA}|}{|T_{aug}|}=\frac{\#\ augmented\ instances}{\#\ instances}\text{ in }T_{aug},

where Ta​u​g=A​u​g​m​e​n​t​(Tb​a​s​e,fi,j,Pk)subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔𝐴𝑢𝑔𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑡subscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒subscript𝑓𝑖𝑗subscript𝑃𝑘T_{aug}=Augment(T_{base},f_{i,j},P_{k}) indicates that Ta​u​gsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔T_{aug} is produced by augmenting the feature fi,jsubscript𝑓𝑖𝑗f_{i,j} to the base table, following the path Pksubscript𝑃𝑘P_{k}. Intuitively, I​Q​(Ta​u​g)𝐼𝑄subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔IQ(T_{aug}) ranges from 0 to 1.

Decomposition of UG. We argue that the utility gain (U​G𝑈𝐺UG) can be expressed by the multiplication of feature importance (F​I𝐹𝐼FI) and integration quality (I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ), i.e., U​G​(Ta​u​g)=F​I​(fi,j)×I​Q​(Ta​u​g)𝑈𝐺subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔𝐹𝐼subscript𝑓𝑖𝑗𝐼𝑄subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔UG(T_{aug})=FI(f_{i,j})\times IQ(T_{aug}). To prove this hypothesis, we will discuss (1) how to estimate the utility score of an augmented table with missing feature values (Theorem 3.3), and (2) the error bound of utility score estimation (Theorem 3.5).

Lemma 3.3.

U​S​(Ta​u​g)𝑈𝑆subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔US(T_{aug}) is the weighted average of U​S​(non-NA)𝑈𝑆non-NA\ US(\textit{non-NA}) and U​S​(NA),𝑈𝑆NAUS(\textit{NA}), namely, U​S​(Ta​u​g)=p×U​S​(non-NA)+(1−p)×U​S​(NA)𝑈𝑆subscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔𝑝𝑈𝑆non-NA1𝑝𝑈𝑆NAUS(T_{aug})=p\times US(\textit{non-NA})+(1-p)\times US(\textit{NA}), where p𝑝p denotes the integration quality measurement for simplicity purposes.

Proof.

Without loss of generality, we choose the classification accuracy as the utility score. By definition, the classification accuracy for non-NA and NA in Ta​u​gsubscript𝑇𝑎𝑢𝑔T_{aug} is:

U​S​(non-NA)=C​Pnon-NA|non-NA|​ and ​U​S​(NA)=C​PNA|N​A|,𝑈𝑆non-NA𝐶subscript𝑃non-NAnon-NA and 𝑈𝑆NA𝐶subscript𝑃NA𝑁𝐴US(\textit{non-NA})=\frac{CP_{\textit{non-NA}}}{|\textit{non-NA}|}\text{ and }US(\textit{NA})=\frac{CP_{\textit{NA}}}{|NA|},

With Theorem 3.7, we establish a theoretical foundation to transform the problem of utility gain maximization into two sub-problems that are more tractable individually. In the following sections, we will describe integration quality and feature importance estimation and an optimized search algorithm that effectively prunes the feature augmentation space based on the properties of integration quality and feature importance.

4. Integration Quality & Feature Importance Estimation

The utility gain has been shown to have a linear relationship with integration quality (I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ) and feature importance (F​I𝐹𝐼FI) in Theorem 3.6. However, both I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ and F​I𝐹𝐼FI are computational expensive to obtain as they require resource intensive joins and model training, particularly when dealing with a large number of features and their associated join paths. As a result, estimating I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ and F​I𝐹𝐼FI to avoid costly joins and model training becomes imperative. In this section, we delves into our proposed solution for I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ and F​I𝐹𝐼FI estimation as well as data selection strategy for estimation model training.

4.1. Integration Quality Estimation

According to Definition 3.2, the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ of a join path, P=Tb​a​s​e⋈0,1T1⋈1,2T2​⋯⋈n−1,nTn𝑃subscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒subscript⋈01subscript𝑇1subscript⋈12subscript𝑇2⋯subscript⋈𝑛1𝑛subscript𝑇𝑛P=T_{base}\bowtie_{0,1}T_{1}\bowtie_{1,2}T_{2}\cdots\bowtie_{n-1,n}T_{n}, is determined by the number of instances in Tb​a​s​esubscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒T_{base} that can be augmented by the instances in the feature column cn,jsubscript𝑐𝑛𝑗c_{n,j} from Tnsubscript𝑇𝑛T_{n}. This essentially boils down to the sequence of join operations in a path. Inspired by cardinality estimation in database systems (Sun and Li, 2019; Kwon et al., 2022), we introduce a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM)-based model designed specifically to estimate the integration quality of a given join path. The idea is to leverage the pairwise table features and statistics to estimate the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ without materializing the join. In the following, we introduce the input features extracted from join operations for LSTM network training.

Transitivity. Intuitively, the transitivity of a join between two tables, denoted as T1⋈1,2T2subscript⋈12subscript𝑇1subscript𝑇2T_{1}\bowtie_{1,2}T_{2}, indicates the number of unique join keys in T2subscript𝑇2T_{2} that can be found in T1subscript𝑇1T_{1}. We formally define it as {Ti.ci,j}∩{Ti+1.ci+1,j}{Ti+1.ci+1,j}\frac{\{T_{i}.c_{i,j}\}\ \cap\ \{T_{i+1}.c_{i+1,j}\}}{\{T_{i+1}.c_{i+1,j}\}}, where {Ti.ci,j}formulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑖subscript𝑐𝑖𝑗\{T_{i}.c_{i,j}\} denotes the set of keys in Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i} that can join with the set of keys in Ti+1subscript𝑇𝑖1T_{i+1}. For instance, if the join keys {T1.c1,2}formulae-sequencesubscript𝑇1subscript𝑐12\{T_{1}.c_{1,2}\} are {1,2,…,100} and {T2.c2,2}formulae-sequencesubscript𝑇2subscript𝑐22\{T_{2}.c_{2,2}\} are {81,82,…,120}, then the transitivity between T1subscript𝑇1T_{1} and T2subscript𝑇2T_{2} is 50%. And the transitivity of a join path can be aggregated by multiplying pairwise transitivity of each join operation. For a join path P=Tb​a​s​e⋈0,1T1⋈1,2T2𝑃subscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒subscript⋈01subscript𝑇1subscript⋈12subscript𝑇2P=T_{base}\bowtie_{0,1}T_{1}\bowtie_{1,2}T_{2}, where T​r​a​n​s​i​t​i​v​i​t​y​(Tb​a​s​e⋈0,1T1)=20%𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑖𝑡𝑖𝑣𝑖𝑡𝑦subscript⋈01subscript𝑇𝑏𝑎𝑠𝑒subscript𝑇1percent20Transitivity(T_{base}\bowtie_{0,1}T_{1})=20\% and T​r​a​n​s​i​t​i​v​i​t​y​(T1⋈1,2T2)=50%𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑖𝑡𝑖𝑣𝑖𝑡𝑦subscript⋈12subscript𝑇1subscript𝑇2percent50Transitivity(T_{1}\bowtie_{1,2}T_{2})=50\%, the transitivity of P𝑃P is 20% ×\times 50% = 10%.

Transitivity is a critical feature when the join keys are uniformly and independently distributed. However, it may not be sufficient when the assumptions of uniformity and independence of join keys do not hold. To mitigate this limitation, we introduce additional features associated with join operations.

Variance. The variance of a join Ti⋈i,jTjsubscript⋈𝑖𝑗subscript𝑇𝑖subscript𝑇𝑗T_{i}\bowtie_{i,j}T_{j} is defined as

Var(Ti​j.ck)=1|Ti​j.ck|∑l=1n(xl−μ)2,Var(T_{ij}.c_{k})=\frac{1}{|T_{ij}.c_{k}|}\sum_{l=1}^{n}(x_{l}-\mu)^{2},

where Ti​jsubscript𝑇𝑖𝑗T_{ij} is the joined table, cksubscript𝑐𝑘c_{k} is the join column between Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i} and Tjsubscript𝑇𝑗T_{j}, xlsubscript𝑥𝑙x_{l} is the instance cksubscript𝑐𝑘c_{k}, and μ=1|Ti​j.ck|​∑l=1nxl\mu=\frac{1}{|T_{ij}.c_{k}|}\sum_{l=1}^{n}x_{l}. Intuitively, a small variance implies a lack of diversity in join results, signifying potential bias that compromises transitivity in subsequent joins.

Entropy. The entropy of a join Ti⋈i,jTjsubscript⋈𝑖𝑗subscript𝑇𝑖subscript𝑇𝑗T_{i}\bowtie_{i,j}T_{j} is defined as

Ent(Ti​j.ck)=−∑l=1𝒳P(xl)⋅log(1−P(xl)),Ent(T_{ij}.c_{k})=-\sum_{l=1}^{\mathcal{X}}P(x_{l})\cdot\log(1-P(x_{l})),

where Ti​jsubscript𝑇𝑖𝑗T_{ij} is the joined table, cksubscript𝑐𝑘c_{k} is the join column between Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i} and Tjsubscript𝑇𝑗T_{j}, and 𝒳𝒳\mathcal{X} denotes the unique values in the join column cksubscript𝑐𝑘c_{k}. While variance is suitable for numeric columns, entropy can serve as a complementary feature for textual and categorical columns.

KL-divergence. This metric quantifies the column distribution difference before and after a join, defined as

KL(Tj.ck,Ti​j.ck′)=∑x∈𝒳P(x)⋅log(P​(x)Q​(x)),KL(T_{j}.c_{k},T_{ij}.c^{\prime}_{k})=\sum_{x\in\mathcal{X}}P(x)\cdot\log(\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}),

where Tj.ckformulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑗subscript𝑐𝑘T_{j}.c_{k} is the column before join, Ti​j.ck′formulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑖𝑗subscriptsuperscript𝑐′𝑘T_{ij}.c^{\prime}_{k} is the column after join, and 𝒳𝒳\mathcal{X} denotes the unique values in a categorical column Tj.ckformulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑗subscript𝑐𝑘T_{j}.c_{k} or the binning of a numeric column Tj.ckformulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑗subscript𝑐𝑘T_{j}.c_{k}. A large KL-divergence indicates potential bias introduced by the join.

Pearson Correlation Coefficient. This metric is a normalized measurement of the covariance, capturing the positive or negative linearity between two join columns. The Pearson Correlation Coefficient can be computed as

PC(Ti.cj,Ti+1.ck)=cov(Ti.cj)var(Ti.cj)var(Ti+1.ck),PC(T_{i}.c_{j},T_{i+1}.c_{k})=\frac{cov(T_{i}.c_{j})}{\sqrt{var(T_{i}.c_{j})var(T_{i+1}.c_{k})}},

where Ti.cjformulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑖subscript𝑐𝑗T_{i}.c_{j} and Ti+1.ckformulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑖1subscript𝑐𝑘T_{i+1}.c_{k} are two join columns in Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i} and Ti+1subscript𝑇𝑖1T_{i+1}.

Mutual Information. Similar to Pearson Correlation Coefficient, mutual information quantifies the shared information between two columns, which can be computed as

MI(Ti.cj,Ti+1.ck)=∑x∈Ti.cj∑y∈Ti+1.ckP(x,y)log(P​(x,y)P​(x)​P​(y)),MI(T_{i}.c_{j},T_{i+1}.c_{k})=\sum_{x\in T_{i}.c_{j}}\sum_{y\in T_{i+1}.c_{k}}P(x,y)log(\frac{P(x,y)}{P(x)P(y)}),

where Ti.cjformulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑖subscript𝑐𝑗T_{i}.c_{j} and Ti+1.ckformulae-sequencesubscript𝑇𝑖1subscript𝑐𝑘T_{i+1}.c_{k} are two join columns in Tisubscript𝑇𝑖T_{i} and Ti+1subscript𝑇𝑖1T_{i+1}, respectively. Mutual information evaluates both linear and non-linear relationships between two join columns.

We use the above feature characteristics of join operations to train a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) model for I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ estimation. The LSTM architecture is chosen due to its lightweight yet powerful capability in capturing the inherent order and dependencies within a sequence of joins in a join path. As depicted in Figure 5, the features, namely V​a​r𝑉𝑎𝑟Var, E​n​t𝐸𝑛𝑡Ent, K​L𝐾𝐿KL, P​C𝑃𝐶PC and M​I𝑀𝐼MI, are concatenated together to represent each join operation Ti⋈i,jTjsubscript⋈𝑖𝑗subscript𝑇𝑖subscript𝑇𝑗T_{i}\bowtie_{i,j}T_{j}. Note that we use the feature column fi,jsubscript𝑓𝑖𝑗f_{i,j} instead of the join column in T4subscript𝑇4T_{4} to compute the above features as it determines the ultimate I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ.

The training objective of the LSTM network using Mean Squared Error (MSE) as the loss function can be represented as follows:

minθ⁡1N​∑i=1N(yi−y^i​(θ))2,subscript𝜃1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑦𝑖subscript^𝑦𝑖𝜃2\min_{\theta}\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i}(\theta))^{2},

where N𝑁N is the number of training examples, yisubscript𝑦𝑖y_{i} is the true I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ for the i𝑖i-th join path sample, and θ𝜃\theta denotes the parameters of the LSTM model, and y^i​(θ)subscript^𝑦𝑖𝜃\hat{y}_{i}(\theta) is the predicted value by the model parameterized by θ𝜃\theta. The training objective is to minimize the MSE loss by adjusting the weights of the LSTM. The method of selecting data points for training the LSTM network will be described in Section 4.3.

4.2. Feature Importance Estimation

Feature importance estimation has been studied (Lundberg and Lee, 2017; Hooker et al., 2018; Škrlj et al., 2020) in recent years. However, these methods are often computationally expensive and model specific. Hence we introduce a simple and effective clustering-based method to estimate the feature importance. The intuition is that features with similar representations in the embedding space tend to have a similar impact (i.e., feature importance) on the ML task (Lundberg and Lee, 2017; Galhotra et al., 2023). The clustering algorithm exploits this observation to compute the representative features’ F​I𝐹𝐼FI in each cluster and estimate F​I𝐹𝐼FI of other features based on their proximity to the representative ones, which leads to substantial computational savings. In the following, we explain four steps to estimate feature importance in detail.

Feature Representation. The representation of a feature column ci,jsubscript𝑐𝑖𝑗c_{i,j} consists of two parts: (1) column metadata, and (2) column data instances. We use a pre-trained language model (PLM) such as BERT (Devlin et al., 2018) to generate the embeddings of column metadata such as column names, column semantic types, column description, if available. For data instances in a feature column, we sample the column, serialize the sample data, and use a PLM to generate the embeddings as well. Finally, we concatenate the embeddings of both column metadata and data instances as the feature representation.

Feature Clustering. We design the clustering method based on DBSCAN (Ester et al., 1996). To be specific, we first randomly select an unexplored feature and check the number of features that lie within its ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-neighborhood, where ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon denotes the threshold of cosine similarity between two feature representations. Then we check if the ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-neighborhood of this selected feature contains at least m𝑚m features. If so we form a cluster by adding all unexplored features within the selected feature’s ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-neighborhood. We iterate this process until all features have been assigned to a cluster. Unlike DBSCAN, we do not consider any feature as noise. Namely, the remaining unexplored features will be considered as clusters of their own. The advantage of this lightweight method is that it bounds the similarity between the centroid feature and other candidate features within a cluster, i.e., c​o​s​(R​e​p​r​(c​e​n​t​r​o​i​d),R​e​p​r​(c​a​n​d​i​d​a​t​ei))≤ϵ𝑐𝑜𝑠𝑅𝑒𝑝𝑟𝑐𝑒𝑛𝑡𝑟𝑜𝑖𝑑𝑅𝑒𝑝𝑟𝑐𝑎𝑛𝑑𝑖𝑑𝑎𝑡subscript𝑒𝑖italic-ϵcos(Repr(centroid),Repr(candidate_{i}))\leq\epsilon.

Compute F​I𝐹𝐼FI. According to Definition 3.1, we need to follow one or more join paths to integrate a feature to the base table in order to compute its F​I𝐹𝐼FI. Naively, one could utilize all join paths between the base table and the feature table to obtain its maximum F​I𝐹𝐼FI, which is very costly. In Section 4.3, we will introduce a data selection strategy that chooses features and their associated join paths for both F​I𝐹𝐼FI computation and LSTM network training.

Estimate F​I𝐹𝐼FI for Unseen Features. For a unseen feature, we estimate its F​I𝐹𝐼FI by a weighted average over the F​I𝐹𝐼FI of its surrounding features in the same feature cluster. Precisely, we have

F​I​(c)=1|N|​∑n=1NF​I​(cn)⋅c​o​s​(c,cn),𝐹𝐼𝑐1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑛1𝑁⋅𝐹𝐼subscript𝑐𝑛𝑐𝑜𝑠𝑐subscript𝑐𝑛FI(c)=\frac{1}{|N|}\sum_{n=1}^{N}FI(c_{n})\cdot cos(c,c_{n}),

where c𝑐c denotes the unseen feature, N𝑁N denotes the set of features with known F​I𝐹𝐼FI in the same cluster, and c​o​s​(⋅)𝑐𝑜𝑠⋅cos(\cdot) represents the cosine similarity between the unseen feature and its neighboring feature. For example, Figure 6 illustrates f1,2subscript𝑓12f_{1,2}’s ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-neighborhood. The distances between the features are calculated using cosine similarity over their feature representations. The F​I𝐹𝐼FI scores of the feature represented in orange circles f1,2subscript𝑓12f_{1,2}, f2,4subscript𝑓24f_{2,4} and f3,6subscript𝑓36f_{3,6} are known. The F​I𝐹𝐼FI scores of the unseen features f4,2subscript𝑓42f_{4,2} and f5,3subscript𝑓53f_{5,3} (green circles) are estimated by referring to the three explored features.

4.3. Data Selection for Estimation

Now we introduce an effective data selection strategy for I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ model training and F​I𝐹𝐼FI estimation, both of which require expensive join executions according to the chosen join paths. In addition, F​I𝐹𝐼FI needs to feed the augmented table to an AutoML framework (e.g., AutoGluon) to obtain the actual feature importance. Hence our goal is to choose high quality data points to serve both I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ and F​I𝐹𝐼FI estimations, in the form of feature-path (fi,jsubscript𝑓𝑖𝑗f_{i,j}, Pksubscript𝑃𝑘P_{k}) pairs. Ideally, the selected data points should have two desired properties. First, the selected integration paths should have a good coverage over all joins among any candidate tables and the base table. The covered joins can be stitched together to accurately estimate unexplored integration paths. Second, the selected features should be evenly distributed across all feature clusters. The number of features chosen from one cluster should be proportioned to the size of the cluster.

To achieve two properties above, we consider the following factors regarding a feature-path pair and propose a weight function to rank all feature-path pairs.

  1. (1)

    Single join path coverage (P​C𝑃𝐶PC) represents how much a join path has been explored. This is measured by the ratio between the number of join edges in a join path that have been explored and the total number of join edges in the path.

  2. (2)

    l𝑙l-hop join path group coverage (P​G​C𝑃𝐺𝐶PGC) represents the number of join paths of a length l𝑙l that have been fully explored. This is measured by the ratio between the number of fully explored l𝑙l-hop join paths and the total number of l𝑙l-hop paths.

  3. (3)

    Feature cluster coverage (F​C𝐹𝐶FC) represents the number of features that have been examined in a feature cluster. This is measured by the ratio between the number of tested features and the total number of features in a cluster.

Note that all the above factors range between [0, 1] and a lower value of each factor indicates that a path or a feature should be explored. Hence the weight function is defined as

(8) w​(fi,j,Pk)=P​C×P​G​C×F​C.𝑤subscript𝑓𝑖𝑗subscript𝑃𝑘𝑃𝐶𝑃𝐺𝐶𝐹𝐶w(f_{i,j},P_{k})=PC\times PGC\times FC.

We assign a score to each feature-path pair using this weight function, rank them in an ascending order to select the one with the smallest weight in each iteration. After each iteration, we update the weights, re-rank the feature-path pairs and continue the selection until a given budget is exhausted. Algorithm 1 details the greedy data point selection method.

Algorithm 1 first initializes several data structures including the ones to store the intermediate states of single join path coverage, l𝑙l-hop join path group coverage, feature cluster coverage, and the weights for all unselected feature-path pairs (Lines 1-7). Then the feature-path pair with the smallest weight is chosen and removed from the set of unselected pairs (Lines 9-11). Note that we randomly select one feature-path pair if there are multiple ones with the smallest weight. Once a feature-path pair is chosen, the join path coverage, join path group coverage, and feature cluster coverage are updated accordingly (Lines 12-17). The weights of the remaining unselected pairs are recomputed based on Equation 8 (Lines 18-20). We iterate this process until the given budget is exhausted or all feature-path pairs are selected.

5. Feature Search and Integration

In this section, we present FeatNavigator’s search algorithm that efficiently and effectively exploits the integration quality and feature importance estimations to identify an augmentation plan that maximizes the utility gain of a ML task.

5.1. Join Graph Model

We first introduce FeatNavigator join graph model to capture the search space of all integration plans.

Definition 5.1 (FeatNavigator Join Graph).

A FeatNavigator join graph 𝒢=(V,E)𝒢𝑉𝐸\mathcal{G}=(V,E) is a unweighted and undirected graph with a set of vertices and a set of edges. A vertex v∈V𝑣𝑉v\in V represents a table, consisting of a set of features F={f1,…,fn}𝐹subscript𝑓1…subscript𝑓𝑛F=\{f_{1},...,f_{n}\}, and an edge e∈E𝑒𝐸e\in E represents a join between two tables.

Given a join graph 𝒢𝒢\mathcal{G}, a source vertex vbsubscript𝑣𝑏v_{b} (i.e., the base table), and a given budget B𝐵B, the goal is to identify no more than B𝐵B features and their respective integration paths in 𝒢𝒢\mathcal{G} to maximize the utility score of the ML task. Note that each path starts from vbsubscript𝑣𝑏v_{b} and ends with a feature fi,jsubscript𝑓𝑖𝑗f_{i,j} associated with a vertex visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}.

Naively, we can follow the breadth-first search (BFS) approach to enumerate all integration paths from vbsubscript𝑣𝑏v_{b}. For a path Pjsubscript𝑃𝑗P_{j} leading to visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}, we form feature-path pairs for all features in visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}. Among all feature-path pairs, we generate all possible candidate combinations with ≤Babsent𝐵\leq B features. The utility score of each candidate combination is computed based on the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ and F​I𝐹𝐼FI estimation. The combination with the maximum utility score represents the optimal solution to the feature augmentation problem. While this naive solution guarantees an optimal solution, it suffers from the combinatorial explosion problem. Specifically, real-world datasets often consist of many candidate tables and join relationships, resulting in a dense join graph. For instance, the School dataset from our experiments has over 10,000 join paths. Worse yet, with n𝑛n candidate features, a budget of at most selecting B𝐵B of them, and on average m𝑚m integration paths for each feature, the number of combinations is ∑i=1Bm⋅(ni)superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝐵⋅𝑚binomial𝑛𝑖\sum_{i=1}^{B}m\cdot\binom{n}{i} (e.g., the School dataset has more than 108superscript10810^{8} combinations).

5.2. Search and Refinement

We introduce two pruning principles below to progressively reduce the search space, preventing the search explosion in the early stage without sacrificing the quality of feature augmentation.

Pruning Principle 1 (I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ Monotonicity). Based on Definition 3.2, the integration quality monotonically decreases as a path extends. In other words, if the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ of a path P𝑃P is too low, it is not beneficial to explore any path that has P𝑃P as its prefix. This fundamental principle is critical for path exploration with early termination.

Pruning Principle 2 (F​I𝐹𝐼FI Lower Bound). If the feature importance of a feature fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} is too low, then fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} and all integration paths to fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} can be safely pruned. The rationale behind this principle is based on Theorem 3.6. Specifically, if fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i}’s F​I𝐹𝐼FI is too low, its U​G𝑈𝐺UG would still be negligible even there were a perfect integration path (i.e., I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ = 1). Note that the lower bound of F​I𝐹𝐼FI can be progressively increased as we explore the search space and identify more useful features.

Search with Progressive Pruning. Leveraging these two pruning principles, we introduce FeatNavigator’s search algorithm (Algorithm 2) for feature selection and their corresponding join path exploration. Algorithm 2 employs a BFS-based approach to identify feature candidates and their integration paths iteratively. It starts with the base table (Line 2) and iteratively extends its search to k𝑘k-hop features (Lines 4-25).

During this process, we maintain a min-heap of size H𝐻H that keeps top-H𝐻H candidate feature-path pairs c​a​n​d​i​d​a​t​e​s𝑐𝑎𝑛𝑑𝑖𝑑𝑎𝑡𝑒𝑠candidates, sorted by the U​G𝑈𝐺UG score in a descending order (Line 3). Note that the heap size H𝐻H is larger than the feature budget B𝐵B so as to maintain a superset of candidates for further refinement. In practice, we set H𝐻H to a multiple of B𝐵B. We then iterate through each k𝑘k-hop path in Pc​u​rsubscript𝑃𝑐𝑢𝑟P_{cur} (line 6), extending the path to include an additional vertex v𝑣v directly connected to the last vertex u𝑢u of the path (Lines 6-12). Subsequently, we compute the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ for the extended path (p′superscript𝑝′p^{\prime}) and discard it if its I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ is below TI​Qsubscript𝑇𝐼𝑄T_{IQ} (Lines 13-14). For the qualified p′superscript𝑝′p^{\prime}, we add it to the set of (k+1)𝑘1(k+1)-hop paths Pn​e​x​tsubscript𝑃𝑛𝑒𝑥𝑡P_{next}, and evaluate the U​G𝑈𝐺UG for each feature on vertex v𝑣v. The feature-path pair with the lowest U​G𝑈𝐺UG score in c​a​n​d​i​d​a​t​e​s𝑐𝑎𝑛𝑑𝑖𝑑𝑎𝑡𝑒𝑠candidates is used as the lower bound. We update c​a​n​d​i​d​a​t​e​s𝑐𝑎𝑛𝑑𝑖𝑑𝑎𝑡𝑒𝑠candidates with the qualified feature-path pair (Lines 16-18). Finally, the algorithm returns the candidate set (Line 26).

Feature Augmentation Refinement. Among the selected feature-path candidates, similar features in the same cluster are expected to have comparable effect on the downstream ML task (Galhotra et al., 2023). In light of this observation, we design a weight decay method to refine the selected feature candidates and to produce the final feature augmentation plan. In essence, this weight decay method aims to mitigate the local optimum incurred by choosing similar features during the search process.

Specifically, the weight decay method relies on a scaling factor using feature similarity to regulate the F​I𝐹𝐼FI on related features, subsequently optimizing the overall efficacy of selected features in the downstream tasks. The weight decay function on a feature f𝑓f is

F​I​(f)=1|N|​∑i=1NF​I​(fi)⋅(1−c​o​s​(f,fi)),𝐹𝐼𝑓1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑁⋅𝐹𝐼subscript𝑓𝑖1𝑐𝑜𝑠𝑓subscript𝑓𝑖FI(f)=\frac{1}{|N|}\sum_{i=1}^{N}FI(f_{i})\cdot(1-cos(f,f_{i})),

where N𝑁N represents the set of already chosen features in the same cluster. The closer a feature to the other chosen features in the same cluster, the more penalty it receives. In the refinement process, we iteratively choose the feature-path pair with the maximum U​G𝑈𝐺UG and update the U​G𝑈𝐺UG of the remaining pairs based on the equation above. After B𝐵B iterations, we select top-B𝐵B feature-path pairs as the feature augmentation plan.

Algorithm 3 illustrates the refinement strategy in detail. It first initializes the estimated U​G𝑈𝐺UG based on I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ and F​I𝐹𝐼FI of each candidate feature-path pair (Lines 2-4). During each iteration, it performs two key steps: (1) among unselected feature-path pairs, it selects the feature and corresponding path with the highest estimated U​G𝑈𝐺UG (Line 9); and (2) it updates the estimated U​G𝑈𝐺UG for remaining feature-path pairs based on the above equation (Line 13). This adjustment indicates that a higher similarity between a unselected feature and the already chosen ones leads to a lower U​G𝑈𝐺UG value for the unselected feature, implying a reduced contribution to the ML task. Finally, the selected feature-path pairs s​e​l​e​c​t​e​d𝑠𝑒𝑙𝑒𝑐𝑡𝑒𝑑selected are returned after a given feature budget B𝐵B is exhausted (Line 16).

6. Experimental Evaluation

6.1. Experimental Setup

Datasets. We evaluate FeatNavigator over five public datasets by performing classification and regression tasks. All five datasets are composed of base tables provided by Kaggle and the DARPA Data Driven Discovery of Models (D3M)777https://datadrivendiscovery.org/about-d3m/. Given a base table, we searched open source datasets for joinable tables using NYU Auctus (Castelo et al., 2021) to identify candidate tables for augmentation purpose.

    DonorsChoose888https://www.kaggle.com/c/donorschoose-application-screening is a Kaggle dataset for a classification task. The target prediction is whether or not a DonorsChoose proposal was accepted. We identified 122 candidate features for augmentation.

    Fraud Detection999https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/ieee-fraud-detection is a Kaggle dataset consisting of over 800 candidate features. The task is to predict whether an online transaction is fraudulent.

  • •

    Poverty consists of socioeconomic features like poverty rates, population change, unemployment rates, and education levels across U.S. States and counties. The task is to predict an index indicating poverty level.

  • •

    Air is a regression dataset from NYU Auctus and google aiming to predict the air quality of a city on a given date.

Note that tables from Kaggle are typically wide, consisting of many features already integrated with base tables. Hence we normalize these wide tables and consequently generate candidate tables with features more than 1-hop away from the original base tables. Table 1 provides the basic information about the three datasets and the numbers of immediate (1-hop) and distant features.

Baselines. We compared FeatNavigator with a variety of baselines, including heuristic-based solutions such as Deep Feature Synthesis and ARDA as well as machine learning-based solutions such as AutoFeature and METAM.

  • •

    Deep Feature Synthesis (DFS) (Kanter and Veeramachaneni, 2015) is a pioneer work that automatically generates features for relational datasets. It utilizes join paths in the data to a base table, and then applies mathematical functions along these paths to create the final features.

  • •

    ARDA (Chepurko et al., 2020) is a feature augmentation system, which employs a variety of heuristics to select top-k𝑘k tables to join and uses a random injection-based feature augmentation to search candidate feature subsets.

  • •

    AutoFeature (Liu et al., 2022) is a reinforcement learning based framework to augment the features following an exploration-exploitation strategy over the search space of candidate tables (features).

  • •

    METAM (Galhotra et al., 2023) is a goal-oriented framework that queries the downstream task with a candidate dataset, using a feedback loop that automatically steers the discovery and augmentation process.

Evaluation Metrics. Since we evaluate FeatNavigator using both classification and regression tasks, we adopt the commonly used metrics for measuring the effectiveness, namely:

F​1=T​PT​P+12​(F​P+F​N),𝐹1𝑇𝑃𝑇𝑃12𝐹𝑃𝐹𝑁F1=\frac{TP}{TP+\frac{1}{2}(FP+FN)},

where T​P𝑇𝑃TP, F​P𝐹𝑃FP and F​N𝐹𝑁FN denote the number of true positive, false positive and false negative predictions, respectively. In particular, we report Accuracy for the classification tasks on DonorChoose and School because of the balanced label distribution over the classes. We report F1 for the classification task on Fraud Detection since the label distribution is skew towards the negative classes and typically a fraudulent (positive) case is a more valuable prediction. For the regression tasks, we follow  (Chepurko et al., 2020; Liu et al., 2022) and report the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) or Mean Square Error (MSE) between the estimated and ground truth values:

In ablation studies, we also measure the accuracy of each FeatNavigator’s component by reporting the MAE or MSE. Note that we use AutoGluon to automatically train multiple models (e.g., XGBoost model, KNN model, neural network models, etc.), and then ensemble the models to create the final predictor.

6.2. Baseline Comparison

We first conduct an end-to-end evaluation of FeatNavigator against the state-of-the-art solutions for feature augmentation. In this set of experiments, we study the effectiveness of FeatNavigator on finding the most useful features from candidate tables within a given budget. The budge B𝐵B is defined as the number of features allowed to augment the base table. We vary the budget from 1, 5 to 10 and report the utility measurements of different methods on the datasets. As shown in Table 2, when B>𝐵absentB> 1, FeatNavigator consistently demonstrates superior performance on finding and integrating features that contribute the most to the task on the base table. The reason is that FeatNavigator not only accurately identifies useful features that are different hops away but also exploits these features with high-quality integration paths.

When the budget is extremely limited (i.e., B𝐵B = 1), FeatNavigator is still among the top 2 performing methods. In both DonorChoose and Air datasets, the most useful feature is from an 1-hop candidate table, which also presents high joinability to the base table. And this information is given to ARDA and hence it is able to outperform FeatNavigator. METAM on the Fraud Detection dataset delivers the best performance by finding a 1-hop join path to the most useful feature. FeatNavigator is slightly worse than METAM due to its I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ and F​I𝐹𝐼FI estimation errors amplified by such an extreme budget.

6.3. Ablation Study

To better understand how our key designs of FeatNavigator benefit the overall performance feature augmentation, we conduct extensive ablation studies to evaluate the performance of FeatNavigator’s individual components and their variants.

6.3.1. Effectiveness of FeatNavigator’s Integration Quality Model.

First, we evaluate the accuracy of FeatNavigator’s LSTM-based I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ estimator. The ground truth is established by materializing the join paths and computing the corresponding I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ scores according to Definition 3.2. We measure and report the MSE between the estimated values and the ground truth values. To make sense of the accuracy of the proposed I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ estimator, we compare it against two baselines: (1) multiplication of Transitivity scores between the tables on a join path (named Production), and (2) randomly predicting an I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ score between 0 and 1 (named Random [0,1]). In addition, we include an LSTM-based I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ estimator trained on randomly selected feature-path pairs and vary the number of training pairs.

Overall, FeatNavigator’s LSTM-based I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ estimator achieves the best (lowest) MSE compared to all baselines across three different datasets, as shown in Figure 7. The random estimator performs the worst (highest) MSE. Notably, our method consistently outperforms both Production and Random methods, which empirically verifies the usefulness of the proposed features for our I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ estimator. With the increasing number (from 50 to 1000) of the training join paths |t​p|𝑡𝑝|tp|, our I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ estimator produces more accurate estimations. Note that 1000 training feature-path pairs only account for approximately 0.1% of all possible pairs in the smallest dataset (i.e., DonorsChoose). We also observe that random data selection strategy demonstrates competitive performance. It is expected as all test sets are randomly drawn from three datasets, respectively.

We further employ the saliency method (Simonyan et al., 2014) to measure the importance of each input feature to the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ model, by assessing their respective gradient concerning the predicted I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ value. As shown in Figure 8, the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ model benefits the most from Pearson correlation and variance, and the other features also contribute to the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ to varying degrees with different datasets. This confirms that the chosen features are essential to a high-quality I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ estimator in FeatNavigator.

6.3.2. Effectiveness of FeatNavigator’s Feature Importance Estimator.

Second, we evaluate the accuracy of our F​I𝐹𝐼FI estimator. The ground truth is established by materializing the test join paths and computing the corresponding F​I𝐹𝐼FI scores using AutoGluon. We measure and report the MAE between the estimated values and the ground truth values. We also vary the size of the training set from 50 to 1000. To make sense of the MAE of our F​I𝐹𝐼FI estimator, we compare it against three alternative designs: (1) a random sampling method that randomly choose |f|𝑓|f| destination features for estimating F​I𝐹𝐼FI. We ensure that at least one sample is drawn from each cluster; (2) a top centroid-based method that allocate budgets uniformly across clusters. Within each cluster, we select the top central features; and (3) a top cover method that equally distributes budgets across clusters. The objective within each cluster is to identify points that minimize the coverage radius.

Overall, as shown in Figure 9, we observe that FeatNavigator’s estimation quality (i.e., lower MAE) improves with an increasing number of data points collected from feature clusters. FeatNavigator outperforms the other baselines on School, Fraud Detection and Air datasets, and its performance on DonorsChoose and Poverty is also very close to the best performing top cover method. When the given budget is small (i.e., |f|≤100)|f|\leq 100), the random sampling method is slightly more effective on DonorsChoose and School datasets. In fact, this is consistent with our observation in the above integration quality evaluation. Hence, one could take a hybrid approach that randomly samples the first 50 or 100 feature-path pairs and then adapts to the proposed data selection strategy when establishing the F​I𝐹𝐼FI estimator and the I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ model.

6.3.3. Effectiveness and Efficiency of FeatNavigator’s Search Algorithm.

Third, we evaluate the effectiveness and efficiency of FeatNavigator’s search algorithm. We report the final Accuracy or F1 as well as the compute time spent on search. To make sense of the measurements, we compare FeatNavigator’s search algorithm against two baselines: (1) an exhaustive method that uses BFS to exhaustively search and estimate all possible combinations of destination features and integration paths; and (2) a greedy method that chooses features with highest estimated F​I𝐹𝐼FI for candidate features. For each candidate feature, it further selects the path with the fewest number of joins (i.e., shortest integration path). If more than one integration paths are the shortest, the greedy method picks the one with the highest estimated I​Q𝐼𝑄IQ. In this experiment, we vary the feature budget from 1 to 10, to be consistent with Table 2.

As shown in Table 3, FeatNavigator’s search algorithm significantly outperforms the greedy algorithm and achieves similar performance to the exhaustive algorithm in Accuracy or F1. Regarding the efficiency, FeatNavigator’s search algorithm also achieves 2-5 times speedup compared to the exhaustive algorithm. Moreover, FeatNavigator’s compute time, on average, increases 2% when increasing the feature budget from 1 to 10. This shows that FeatNavigator’s search algorithm is scalable to a large number of features allowed for augmentation.

We further evaluate the performance of FeatNavigator’s search algorithm by varying heap sizes H𝐻H from 5 to 100 and report the final model performance and the search compute time. As shown in Figure 10, the model performance shows solid improvements with an increasing heap size, while the latency only increases sub-linearly. This showcases that FeatNavigator’s search and refinement algorithms are effective and efficient.

6.4. End-to-End Latency

In Table 4, we report the end-to-end latency of FeatNavigator and other baselines over three datasets. The feature budget is set to 10 to be consistent with Table 2. Specifically, FeatNavigator is 2.1% and 18.4% faster than METAM on Fraud Detection and School datasets, and 6.2% faster than ARDA on DonorsChoose dataset. This shows that FeatNavigator not only delivers the best model performance but also has lower latency compared to the best performing baselines.

7. Related Work

Feature Augmentation. Automatic feature augmentation has been intensively studied and shown effective for various ML tasks including classification, regression, clustering, etc. Kumar et al. (Kumar et al., 2016) focus on the problem of when to avoid primary key-foreign key join without sacrificing the performance of the model. Deep Feature Synthesis (DFS) (Kanter and Veeramachaneni, 2015) is one of the early work in generating features for relational datasets. DFS follows joinable relationships in the data to a base table, and then sequentially applies mathematical functions along that path to create the final features. ARDA (Chepurko et al., 2020) is a feature augmentation framework that leverages existing data discovery tools (Fernandez et al., 2018) to score the candidate tables and uses a heuristic algorithm to select features. Hence, the performance of ARDA heavily relies on the scores given by Aurum, which are not always accurate as they are not model-aware.

Recently, AutoFeature (Liu et al., 2022) leverages reinforcement learning (RL) for feature augmentation. It uses either a multi-armed bandits or a branch Deep Q Networks to choose between exploring features that could lead to performance improvement and exploiting features that are rarely selected. METAM (Galhotra et al., 2023) is a goal-oriented framework that also utilizes the multi-arm bandit method for feature discovery and augmentation to achieve the desired performance of a given task. It uses data properties, utility functions from downstream tasks and the given candidate dataset to drive the discovery and augmentation process. Coreset selection (Wang et al., 2022; Chai et al., 2023) aims to select a high-quality coreset without materializing the augmented table and uses weighted gradients of the selected coreset to approximate the full gradient of the entire train dataset.

Feature Selection. Feature selection (Chandrashekar and Sahin, 2014; Li et al., 2017) aims to identify a subset of the most relevant features from a large dataset for a specific ML task, thereby reducing feature dimensionality. In contrast, feature augmentation involves increasing the number of features to enhance the model’s predictive capability. The ranking-based methods evaluate the importance of each feature using statistical metrics like correlation coefficient or mutual information with the labels (Guyon and Elisseeff, 2003) and then select the top relevant features. However, ranking-based methods may yield a sub-optimal subset with highly correlated variables, where a smaller subset would suffice.

Sequential selection and heuristic search algorithms optimize a utility gain objective function for feature subset evaluation. Due to the NP-hard nature of evaluating 2Nsuperscript2𝑁2^{N} subsets, these methods find sub-optimal subsets heuristically. Sequential algorithms (Pudil et al., 1994) either add or remove features from an initial empty (or full) set until the utility gain is maximized, using a criterion to incrementally enhance the utility gain with fewer features. Heuristic algorithms (Goldberg, 2013), on the other hand, explore different subsets, either by searching within a space or generating solutions to optimize the utility gain. More recently, Cherepanova et al. (Cherepanova et al., 2023) propose an input-gradient-based analogue of Lasso for neural networks that outperforms classical feature selection methods on challenging problems such as selecting from corrupted or second-order features in the tabular deep learning setting. Liu et al. (Liu et al., 2023) reformulate feature selection with a RL framework by regarding each feature as an agent.

Table Discovery. Table discovery systems (Fernandez et al., 2018; Zhu et al., 2019; Zhang and Ives, 2020; Dong et al., 2023; Khatiwada et al., 2023a; Hu et al., 2023; Fan et al., 2023) find joinable and unionable tables from data repositories to boost downstream applications, such as related table discovery, table QA, and ML models. Modern techniques (Zhang and Ives, 2020; Gong et al., 2023) allow users to interactively search useful joinable datasets by specifying requirements in the form of data profiles or examples. However, without the information of ML models, it is difficult to identify which tables and join paths are useful to the downstream ML models.

8. Conclusion

In this paper, we propose a framework FeatNavigator for automatic feature augmentation. FeatNavigator tackles the intractable problem of feature augmentation by decomposing it into feature importance and integration quality. We design a lightweight clustering-based method for feature importance estimation and an LSTM-based integration quality model. We further introduce an efficient feature path search algorithm that exploits both estimated feature importance and integration quality to identify high-quality features and their optimized join paths for integration under a given budget. Our experiments on three public datasets demonstrate the effectiveness of FeatNavigator.
